  "title": "山核桃大街谋杀案",
  "source_file": "data\\raw\\detectiveqa\\novel_data_en\\121-山核桃大街谋杀案-阿加莎克里斯蒂.txt",
  "chunk_index": 25,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot visits Valerie Hobhouse at 26 Walnut Street on a Sunday to discuss the ongoing investigation. Jerome, a resident, leads Poirot to Valerie’s spacious and tastefully decorated room, which contains furniture that Poirot observes is not original to the residence. Valerie, a stakeholder for a beauty salon called Sedna Goddess who travels frequently to Europe, appears tired and anxious, noting that she was questioned by Inspector Sharp the previous day.\n\nDuring their conversation, Poirot reveals that he had the stolen engagement ring belonging to Patricia Lean examined by a jeweler. He discloses his discovery that the large gemstone in the ring is not a diamond, but a white zircon. While Valerie suggests that Patricia may have replaced a lost diamond with a cheaper stone due to financial difficulties, Poirot proposes a different theory: the diamond was deliberately removed and replaced with a zircon before the ring was returned.\n\nPoirot accuses Valerie of stealing the diamond. He bases his reasoning on the circumstances under which the ring was \"discovered\" in her soup bowl. He points out that because the soup was brought to the table covered with a lid, only the person serving the food or the person eating it could have placed the ring inside. Poirot concludes that Jerome, the server, did not do it, and instead accuses Valerie of staging the discovery in her own bowl for her own amusement and sense of humor, thereby exposing her involvement.",
  "summary_whitespace_tokens": 240,
